@article{Hay2000pulselength,
    abstract = {We compare high-order harmonic generation in gas jets of benzene; cyclohexane; and xenon using <800-nm laser pulses of 70 fs and 240 fs duration. The harmonic intensities of the 7th to 15th orders are studied as a function of laser intensity in the range 5 10 13  to 5 10 15  W cm -2 . Using 240-fs pulses; the dependence of the harmonic intensity on the laser intensity of the organic molecules exhibits significant deviations from the behavior of atoms; and shows strong evidence for harmonic generation from molecular fragments as well as the parent molecule. When the pulse duration is reduced to 70 fs; the intensity dependences of the harmonics are similar to those of xenon. This is attributed to the significant reduction in dissociation occurring during the shorter pulse and suggests that high-order harmonic generation in the ultrafast regime will be important in the understanding of molecular electron dynamics in strong fields.},
